outcomes.title: Tangent Planes
outcomes.description: Find equations for tangent planes to surfaces expressed as graphs of two-variable functions and as level sets of three-variable functions.
outcomes.template:
A mysterious function f(x,y) has first partial derivatives

f_x(x,y) = {{fx}}\qquad and

f_y(x,y) = {{fy}}\qquad.

We don't know a formula for f, but we do know that f({{x0}},{{y0}}) = {{z0}}.

Find an equation for the tangent plane to the graph z=f(x,y) at (x_0,y_0)=({{x0}},{{y0}}).

{{fx0}}({{xe}}) + {{fy0}}({{ye}}) - ({{ze}})=0, or {{planelhs}} = {{planerhs}}.

Use linearization to approximate the value of f({{x1}},{{y1}}).

An approximate value is {{z0}}+{{fx0}}({{dx}})+{{fy0}}({{dy}}) = {{z1}}.

Consider the function f(x,y)= {{f}}.

Compute the gradient vector \nabla f(x,y).

Compute \nabla f({{x0}},{{y0}}) and sketch this vector, with its initial point at P({{x0}},{{y0}}), on the contour plot of f shown below.

The gradient at the indicated point is \nabla f( {{x0}},{{y0}} ) = \bigl\langle {{fx0}},{{fy0}} \bigr\rangle.
